Title: IT_SD_SENSITIVITY_LEVELS
Owner: IT Department
Last Reviewed: 03-26-2026
Status: Active
Sensitivity Level: Level 1: Public / Internal General
Scope: 
The purpose of this document is to set a sensitivity level standard to ensure that proprietary &/OR personally identifiable information is protected while maintaining that generalized information is still reasonably accessible. 


🟢 Level 1: Public / Internal General
Definition: General operational procedures that contain no proprietary configuration data or security-sensitive info.
•	Access: All employees (IT and non-IT).
•	Examples: * How to request a new hardware peripheral.
o	Standard software installation guides for end-users.
o	Basic troubleshooting for office Wi-Fi.
•	Data Content: Public-facing links, screenshots of standard UI, and general "how-to" text.

🟡 Level 2: Internal IT (Standard)
Definition: The "bread and butter" of our department. Contains internal technical workflows that assume a level of IT knowledge.
•	Access: All members of the IT Department.
•	Examples: Standard VM creation steps.
o	Patch management schedules and workflows.
o	Student account creation/maintenance standards.
•	Data Content: Internal server names, VLAN IDs, and non-privileged service account names. No passwords or credentials.

🟠 Level 3: Confidential / Team Restricted
Definition: Procedures for high-value systems or those governed by compliance (HIPAA, SOC2, PCI). Access is restricted to the specific team members managing the asset.
•	Access: Specific to only our internal IT department.
•	Examples: Critical maintenance information.
o	Firewall/Network configurations.
o	Accessing the HR payroll system backend.
o	Student Billing information/systems.
•	Data Content: IP addresses of production machines, and specific security hardening steps.

🔴 Level 4: Highly Restricted / "Secret"
Definition: Procedures involving the "keys to the kingdom." These runbooks often contain instructions on how to access root-level credentials or bypass standard security in emergencies.
•	Access: Owners of specific processes.
•	Examples: Firewall Panel Credentials.
o	Root CA (Certificate Authority) renewal processes.
o	Direct Database Access.
o	API/Encryption Key Access.
o	General Credential Access as it pertains to each role.
